'''Unpaid workers''' are those who [[employment|work]] without [[wage|pay]]. These may be either members of a [[family]] or [[cooperative]]; [[conscripts]] or [[forced labour]]; [[volunteer]] workers who work for [[charity (practice)|charity]] or [[amusement]];<ref>{{citation |url=http://books.google.com/?id=q5QOAAAAQAAJ |year=1993 |title=Volunteers |isbn=978-0-415-09427-6 |author=Jone L. Pearce}}</ref> [[student]]s who take [[intern]] positions as [[work experience]]; or conventional workers who are not paid because their enterprise is short of [[money]] or subject to [[embezzlement]].
==Unpaid student interns in the United States== There are three quarters of a million unpaid [[internship]] positions in the [[United States]] every year. Internships should provide training for students, not to be used by employers to save costs according to [[labor law]]. Two lawsuits have been recently launched by [[student]]s who claim they were utilized as cheap (free) labor by their so-called [[employer]]s to replace paid-[[worker]]s.<ref>"Fewer unpaid internships in works" USA Today published March 8, page B1</ref>
